"],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braci","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>braz</i>, <i>brace</i>, <i>brase</i> ‘arm’, probably used of someone with a strong arm or with a deformity of the arm."],"variants":[{"name":"Brass","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Birse in Aberdeenshire, metathesized to <i>Brass</i>.","English (Northumberland): variant of   Brace  .","North German: nickname from Middle Low German <i>brās</i> ‘noise, pomp’, a related form of <i>brāsch</i> (see   Braasch  )."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert de Braci was born in 1085, his father, Roger de Arundel, was 45 and his mother, Almodis de la Marche, was 23. He married Rosamond de Novant about 1104, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1111, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1085–1111":"1085–1111","1085–1133":"1